<emphasis id="5295EAFDFFC7D6490FD1FD9E170D3496" box="[1435,1570,626,655]" pageId="17" pageNumber="708">Breeding.</emphasis>
No information.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="28FB6564FFC7D6490FD0FD7919353565" pageId="17" pageNumber="708" type="activity">
<paragraph id="605E36EFFFC7D6490FD0FD7919353565" blockId="17.[1433,2641,307,1012]" pageId="17" pageNumber="708">
<emphasis id="5295EAFDFFC7D6490FD0FD7917A734AF" box="[1434,1672,661,694]" pageId="17" pageNumber="708">Activity patterns.</emphasis>
Eger’s Long-fingered Bat is nocturnal. A day roost was found in a natural rock shelter surrounded by slightly disturbed natural lowland humid forest; caves and even tree holes are probably also used as roosts. Echolocation calls have downward FM signals, with maximum frequencies of 107-123 kHz, minimum frequencies of 48-50 kHz, peak frequencies of 53-2-56-3 kHz, durations of 2-5-3-4 milliseconds, and intervals of 43-2—81-8 milliseconds.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
